-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Loyal
This makes Loyal the likely recipient of both the first- and second-ever RX=
E acknowledgements from the FDA for longevity drug programs for any species=
 =E2=80=94 including humans.
Loyal is making some big (and small) dog moves!
The biotech company focused on canine longevity (and R&D that could eventua=
lly benefit humans) announced that the FDA granted its drug a =E2=80=9Creas=
onable expectation of effectiveness=E2=80=9D in extending senior dogs' life=
spans. Loyal still needs the FDA=E2=80=99s final approval before it hits th=
e market, but the company is still targeting late 2025 availability. The dr=
ug, called LOY-002, will be offered to senior dogs of all sizes (or at leas=
t >14 lbs). Importantly, Loyal=E2=80=99s previous programs focused on older=
, larger dogs and wasn=E2=80=99t available to smaller and medium sized pooc=
hes.
While Loyal can=E2=80=99t really yet make claims on lifespan extension, it =
does comp the drug to a previous study from Purina on caloric restriction t=
hat extended dogs lives 2 years. Dogs can=E2=80=99t be on caloric restricti=
on forever, that=E2=80=99s not sustainable, but taking a beef-flavored LOY-=
002 drug may be scalable to millions of dogs.
Extending the lives of millions of dogs is a good thing. Achieve that and L=
oyal is not only a valuable company, but likely a very loved company. But t=
he company=E2=80=99s ambitions don=E2=80=99t stop at dogs. It wants to buil=
d on its learnings in creating canine longevity programs to build human lon=
gevity programs. And if they achieve that before others, Loyal is likely on=
e of the most valuable and important companies in the world. Bow wow wow.
