From Apple
=E2=80=9CWe are bullish on the future of American innovation, and we=E2=80=
=99re proud to build on our long-standing U.S. investments with this $500 b=
illion commitment to our country=E2=80=99s future,=E2=80=9D said Tim Cook, =
Apple=E2=80=99s CEO. =E2=80=9CFrom doubling our Advanced Manufacturing Fund=
, to building advanced technology in Texas, we=E2=80=99re thrilled to expan=
d our support for American manufacturing. And we=E2=80=99ll keep working wi=
th people and companies across this country to help write an extraordinary =
new chapter in the history of American innovation.=E2=80=9D
$500B! How =E2=80=98bout them apples?!
Apple is committing $500 billion to U.S. investments over the next four yea=
rs, focusing on AI, silicon engineering, and advanced manufacturing. The sc=
heduled investments include a new server manufacturing facility in Houston,=
 expanded chip production in Arizona, and a doubled $10 billion Advanced Ma=
nufacturing Fund. The additional investment is expected to add about 20,000=
 Apple jobs and, in addition, the company is launching a manufacturing acad=
emy in Detroit to train workers in AI and automation.
Why would Apple do this? Besides some obvious genuflecting to the Trump Adm=
inistration, the move to onshore some of its manufacturing infrastructure t=
o the U.S. is intended to increase supply chain resiliency in the face of i=
ncreasingly cooled relationships with China. And maybe to give Tim Cook a l=
ittle power back.
A couple weeks ago, on the Shawn Ryan Show [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
447b0a97-8805-4db6-beb0-0b4998c24972?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Anduril co-founder Palmer Luckey called Coo=
k out for the company=E2=80=99s (necessary but embarrassing) stance on Chin=
a:=20
Like Tim Cook, I have nothing against the guy, personally, but like if I we=
re him, I would feel a little humiliated that I can=E2=80=99t say anything =
about China despite supposedly on paper being one of the most powerful men =
in the world.
=E2=80=A6He=E2=80=99s politically engaged. Imagine what would happen if he =
said something like =E2=80=9CI believe concentration camps are bad.=E2=80=
=9D Like China, on account of the Uighur Muslim issue, would immediately lo=
ck them out of the country. He can=E2=80=99t say that. Isn=E2=80=99t that c=
razy? =20
I=E2=80=99ll stop. Palmer keeps going. Watch it. I started the clip at the =
beginning of the rant.=20
Critics argue that a lot of this is money Apple was going to spend in the U=
S anyway, packaged into a nice, big, round, Trump-pleasing number. That may=
 be the case.=20
But Apple is the most valuable company in the world =E2=80=94 by a margin o=
f, coincidentally, $500B =E2=80=94 and it makes sense for it to continue to=
 invest in its home country, make its supply chains less vulnerable, and (f=
rankly) score a major political win with an administration that values flat=
tery and cooperation above all else. We=E2=80=99ll take the W.=20
And if you hear Tim Cook start making Winnie the Pooh jokes, you=E2=80=99ll=
 know what happened.=20
